        "content": "**How to read this dashboard**\n\nA WAN cut severs a cabinet's uplink. Watch its **INGEST RATE** (top) drop to zero and its **FRESHNESS** climb \u2014 meanwhile the cabinet's **EDGE BUFFER** keeps capturing every message (nothing lost). On **RESTORE**, ingest spikes as the buffer drains upstream and the **CUMULATIVE** count catches up with zero loss and zero duplicates.\n\n**Baseline (now):** every cabinet is connected \u2014 ingest rate (panel 1) shows the cut-target and its two sibling lines all flowing, freshness (panel 2) stays low/green, the edge buffer (panel 3) climbs its normal gentle slope for each corridor cabinet alike, and cumulative totals (panel 4) rise together.\n\n**During a WAN cut** (`democtl cut -cabinet <id>`): the cut cabinet's ingest rate (panel 1) drops straight to zero \u2014 the clearest signal \u2014 while its freshness gap (panel 2) climbs into yellow/red. Its edge buffer (panel 3) keeps climbing at the same steady rate as always \u2014 that's by design, the edge never stops capturing. Its cumulative total (panel 4) flattens.\n\n**On restore** (`democtl restore -cabinet <id>`): ingest (panel 1) spikes as the drained buffer's backlog lands, freshness (panel 2) drops back to green, and the cumulative staircase (panel 4) steps up to cover what was buffered \u2014 **zero events lost, zero duplicated**.",
        "mode": "markdown"
      },
      "title": "About this dashboard",
      "type": "text"
    }
